        <body>
            <div xml:id="KT385-kilavi">
                <p type="edition">vēṟṟu varaivu māṟṟiyatu. </p>


                <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Preventing a marriage to somebody else. </p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="KT385">
                <lg type="edition">
                    <l> palaviṟ cērnta paḻamā riṉakkalai</l>
                    <l> cilaiviṟ kāṉavaṉ centoṭai verīic</l>
                    <l> ceruvuṟu kutiraiyiṟ poṅkic cāra</l>
                    <l> liruvetir nīṭamai tayaṅkap pāyum</l>
                    <l> peruvarai yaṭukkattuk kiḻava ṉeṉṟu</l>
                    <l> maṉṟai yaṉṉa naṭpiṉaṉ</l>
                    <l> putuvōrt tammaviv vaḻuṅka lūrē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <l> The master of the big mountain side,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> where the male of the fruit-eating monkey group joined</l>
                    <l rend="indent8"> by the jackfruit tree,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> frightened by the red arrow <note place="foot">Or: "the
                        straight arrow".</note> of the forest man</l>
                    <l rend="indent7"> with [his] Cilai [wood] bow,</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> is leaping, <note place="foot">As so often the relations are
                        unmarked. I understand kalai as the subject to <term xml:lang="ta">verīi </term>
                        and <term xml:lang="ta">pāyum</term> , but <term xml:lang="ta">amai</term>
                        as subject to <term xml:lang="ta">poṅki</term> and <term xml:lang="ta">
                        tayaṅka</term> .</note> so that the long bamboo[-stems]</l>
                    <l rend="indent7"> of the big bamboo glitter <note place="foot">One possibility
                        to come to terms with two words for bamboo here is to take <term xml:lang="ta">amai</term> as a part of the vetir plant, as is done
                        by T.V.G.</note>
                    </l>
                    <l rend="indent2"> on the slope, prancing like horses in a fight,</l>
                    <l rend="indent9"> – any day</l>
                    <l> he [is] intimate <note place="foot">
                            <term xml:lang="ta">naṭpiṉaṉ</term> is denominative and end of the
                        sentence, unmarked because the next sentence starts with the predicate.</note>
                        [with us] as on that day.</l>
                    <l> Newcomers [has], alas, this noisy village.</l>


                </lg>
            </div>
        </body>
